{"id":"1301.3652","submitter":"Edward Chapin","authors":"Edward L. Chapin, David S. Berry, Andrew G. Gibb, Tim Jenness, Douglas\n  Scott, Remo P. J. Tilanus, Frossie Economou, Wayne S. Holland","title":"SCUBA-2: iterative map-making with the Sub-Millimetre User Reduction\n  Facility","comments":"Revised some terminology in section 2.5, fixed typos, updated\n  references (to match published version in MNRAS). 32 pages, 20 figures, 1\n  table","journal-ref":"Chapin E. L. et al., 2013, MNRAS, 430, 2545","doi":"10.1093/mnras/stt052","report-no":null,"categories":"astro-ph.IM","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  The Submillimetre Common User Bolometer Array 2 (SCUBA-2) is an instrument\noperating on the 15-m James Clerk Maxwell Telescope, nominally consisting of\n5120 bolometers in each of two simultaneous imaging bands centred over 450 and\n850 um. The camera is operated by scanning across the sky and recording data at\na rate of 200 Hz. As the largest of a new generation of multiplexed kilopixel\nbolometer cameras operating in the (sub)millimetre, SCUBA-2 data analysis\nrepresents a significant challenge. We describe the production of maps using\nthe Sub-Millimetre User Reduction Facility (SMURF) in which we have adopted a\nfast, iterative approach to map-making that enables data reduction on single,\nmodern, high-end desktop computers, with execution times that are typically\nshorter than the observing times. SMURF is used in an automated setting, both\nat the telescope for real-time feedback to observers, as well as for the\nproduction of science products for the JCMT Science Archive at the Canadian\nAstronomy Data Centre. Three detailed case studies are used to: (i) explore\nconvergence properties of the map-maker using simple prior constraints (Uranus\n-- a point source); (ii) achieve the white-noise limit for faint point-source\nstudies (extragalactic blank-field survey of the Lockman Hole); and (iii)\ndemonstrate that our strategy is capable of recovering angular scales\ncomparable to the size of the array footprint (approximately 5 arcmin) for\nbright extended sources (star-forming region M17).\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 16 Jan 2013 10:56:55 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Mon, 25 Mar 2013 10:31:49 GMT"}],"update_date":"2013-03-26"}
{"id":"1301.3653","submitter":"Djurdje Cvijovi\\'c","authors":"Djurdje Cvijovic","title":"Higher-order tangent and secant numbers","comments":"10 pages; published","journal-ref":"Computers and Mathematics with Applications, 62 (2011) 1879-1886","doi":"10.1016/j.camwa.2011.06.031","report-no":null,"categories":"math.CA","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  In this paper higher-order tangent numbers and higher-order secant numbers,\n${\\mathscr{T}(n,k)}_{n,k =0}^{\\infty}$ and ${\\mathscr{S}(n,k)}_{n,k\n=0}^{\\infty}$, have been studied in detail. Several known results regarding\n$\\mathscr{T}(n,k)$ and $\\mathscr{S}(n,k)$ have been brought together along with\nmany new results and insights and they all have been proved in a simple and\nunified manner. In particular, it is shown that the higher-order tangent\nnumbers $\\mathscr{T}(n,k)$ constitute a special class of the partial\nmultivariate Bell polynomials and that $\\mathscr{S}(n,k)$ can be computed from\nthe knowledge of $\\mathscr{T}(n,k)$. In addition, a simple explicit formula\ninvolving a double finite sum is deduced for the numbers $\\mathscr{T}(n,k)$ and\nit is shown that $\\mathscr{T}(n,k)$ are linear combinations of the classical\ntangent numbers $T_n$.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 16 Jan 2013 10:59:45 GMT"}],"update_date":"2013-01-17"}
